It depends on the crossover rules you have, a trivial implementation is to have every second element:

	for(std::size_t i = 0; i &lt; array1.size();i++)
	{
		if(i % 2 == 0)
			std::swap(array1[i],array2[i])
	}

Note: This assumes array1 and array2 have the same size.

There is a standard algorithm  [`std::swap_ranges`](https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/algorithm/swap_ranges) designed for this.

```
#include &lt;algorithm&gt;
#include &lt;array&gt;

int main() {
    std::array&lt;int, 3&gt; array1 = { 1, 2, 3 };
    std::array&lt;int, 3&gt; array2 = { 10, 20, 30 };

    const int position = 2;
    std::swap_ranges(array1.begin(), array1.begin() + position, array2.begin());
}
```

