This is specific to the [`MEMORY STATS`][1] redis command. Its result is an array, _&quot;the information about memory usage is provided as metrics and their respective values &quot;_.


Since there is no &quot;predefined&quot; type to model this, simply use a [type-assertion][2] to acquire the slice in Go, iterate over it, and look for the key you&#39;re interested in: `&quot;total.allocated&quot;`. The subsequent slice element will be the value you&#39;re looking for.

This is how you can do it:

    result, err := client.Do(&quot;MEMORY&quot;, &quot;STATS&quot;).Result()
    if err != nil {
        // Handle error
        return
    }
    if stats, ok := result.([]interface{}); ok {
        for i := 0; i &lt; len(stats); i += 2 {
            if stats[i] == &quot;total.allocated&quot; &amp;&amp; i+1 &lt; len(stats) {
                fmt.Println(&quot;total allocated memory:&quot;, stats[i+1])
            }
        }
    }

We can simplify the loop if we loop until `len-1` (instead of `len`), so we don&#39;t have to check if `i+1` is valid index:

	for i, max := 0, len(stats)-1; i &lt; max; i += 2 {
		if stats[i] == &quot;total.allocated&quot; {
			fmt.Println(&quot;total allocated memory:&quot;, stats[i+1])
		}
	}


The value of total allocated memory is a value of type `int64`. If you need it as a number, use another type-assertion:

    allocated := stats[i+1].(int64)

Or to be safe:

    if allocated, ok := stats[i+1].(int64); ok {
        // Use allocated
    }


  [1]: https://redis.io/commands/memory-stats
  [2]: https://golang.org/ref/spec#Type_assertions

